# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: davis-cup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1900 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the first edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The tournament was conceived in 1899 by four members of the Harvard University tennis team, who came up with the idea of challenging the British to a tennis competition.
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Once the idea received the go-ahead from the United States Lawn Tennis Association and the British Lawn Tennis Association, Dwight F.
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Davis, one of the four Harvard players, designed a tournament format and spent money from his own pocket to purchase an appropriate sterling silver trophy from Shreve, Crump & Low.
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The first match between the United States and the British Isles was held at the Longwood Cricket Club in Boston, Massachusetts in 1900.
[src:davis-cup/1900-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The American team, of which Davis was a part, won the first three matches and the Challenge.
[src:davis-cup/1902-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1902 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the second edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1902-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The tie was played at the Crescent Athletic Club in Brooklyn, New York, United States.
[src:davis-cup/1902-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The Crescent Athletic Club was located at Narrows Avenue and 85th Street, site at present of the Fort Hamilton HS Athletic Field.
[src:davis-cup/1903-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1903 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the third edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1903-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The British Isles team returned to the United States to contest the Cup.
[src:davis-cup/1903-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The tie was played at the Longwood Cricket Club in Boston, Massachusetts (the same location as the first competition in 1900).
[src:davis-cup/1903-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The British won 4–1, bringing the Cup to Britain for the first time.
[src:davis-cup/1904-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1904 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the fourth edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**, and the first edition to be played outside American soil.
[src:davis-cup/1904-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] As defending champions, the British Isles team played host to the competition, which featured teams from Belgium and France for the first time.
[src:davis-cup/1904-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Belgium and France would play for the right to challenge the British Isles for the cup.
[src:davis-cup/1904-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The ties were played at Worple Road (the former site of the All England Club) in Wimbledon, London, United Kingdom from 27 June to 5 July.
[src:davis-cup/1904-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Despite Malcolm Whitman giving his word that an American team would enter, the Americans failed to make a challenge before the 7 March deadline.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1905 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the fifth edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] As defending champions, the British Isles team played host to the competition.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The World Group ties were played at Queen's Club in London, England from 13–19 July, and the final was played on 21–24 July.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Britain retained the Cup for their third championship.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Australasia, a combined Australia-New Zealand team, and Austria joined the competition for the first time.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The United States returned after a 1-year hiatus, and France would return for their second year.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] For the first time, a "World Group" tournament was held to determine which team would challenge the British Isles for the cup.
[src:davis-cup/1905-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The match was scratched and the United States advanced to the semifinals as Belgium were unable to field a team due to player illness.
[src:davis-cup/1906-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1906 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the sixth edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1906-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] For the first time, the ties were not all played at the same location.
[src:davis-cup/1906-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The "World Group" ties were played at the Newport Athletic Club in Newport, Monmouthshire, Wales from 7–9 June, and the final was played at Worple Road (the former site of the All England Club) in Wimbledon, London, England on 15–18 June.
[src:davis-cup/1906-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Britain retained the Cup for their fourth championship.
[src:davis-cup/1906-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] 1 Both semifinals were scratched and Australasia and the United States advanced to the final as Austria and France failed to appear.
[src:davis-cup/1907-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The **1907 International Lawn Tennis Challenge** was the seventh edition of what is now known as the **Davis Cup**.
[src:davis-cup/1907-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] After several years of more varied competition, only Australasia and the United States would challenge for the cup.
[src:davis-cup/1907-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] Australasia won both ties, and became the third nation to win the cup.
[src:davis-cup/1907-international-lawn-tennis-challenge] The ties were played at Worple Road (the former site of the All England Club) in Wimbledon, London, England from 13–24 July.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The **Davis Cup** is the premier international team event in men's tennis.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] It is organised by World Tennis and contested annually between teams from over 150 competing countries, making it the world's largest annual team sporting competition.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] It is described by the organisers as the "World Cup of Tennis" and the winners are referred to as the world champions.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The competition began in 1900 as a challenge between Great Britain and the United States.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Initially titled the **International Lawn Tennis Challenge**, it soon became known metonymically after the trophy donated by Dwight F.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Davis; the name was officially changed after Davis' death in 1945.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] By 2023, 155 nations entered teams into the competition.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The most successful country over the history of the competition is the United States (winning 32 titles and finishing as runners-up 29 times).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The most recent champions are Italy, who beat Spain to win their fourth title (and third consecutive one) in 2025.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The women's equivalent of the Davis Cup is the Billie Jean King Cup, formerly known as the Federation Cup (1963–1995) and Fed Cup (1995–2020).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Australia, Italy, Russia, the Czech Republic and the United States are the only countries to have won both Davis Cup and Federation/Fed/Billie Jean King Cup titles in the same year.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The Davis Cup allowed only amateurs and national registered professional players (from 1968) to compete until 1973, five years after the start of the Open Era.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The idea for an event pitting the best British and Americans in competition against one another was most likely first conceived by James Dwight, the first president of the U.S.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] National Lawn Tennis Association when it formed in 1881.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Desperate to assess the development of American players against the renowned British champions, he worked tirelessly to engage British officials in a properly sanctioned match, but failed to do so.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] He nevertheless tried to entice top international (particularly British) talent to the U.S. and sanctioned semi-official tours of the top American players to Great Britain.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] International competitions had been staged for some time before the first Davis Cup match in 1900.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] From 1892, England and Ireland had been competing in an annual national-team-based competition, similar to what would become the standard Davis Cup format, mixing single and doubles matches, and in 1895 England played against France in a national team competition.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] During Larned's tour of the British Isles in 1896, where he competed in several tournaments including the Wimbledon Championships, he was also a spectator for the annual England vs.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] He returned to exclaim that Britain had agreed to send a group of three to the U.S. the following summer, which would represent the first British lawn tennis "team" to compete in the U.S.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Coincidentally, some weeks before Larned left for his British tour, the idea for an international competition was discussed also between leading figures in American lawn tennis—one of whom was tennis journalist E.P.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Fischer—at a tournament in Niagara-on-the-Lake, Ontario.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Davis was in attendance at this tournament, and was thought to have got wind of the idea as it was discussed in the tournament's popular magazine, and Davis's name was mentioned as someone who might 'do something for the game ... put up some big prize, or cup'.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Larned and Fischer met on several occasions that summer and discussed the idea of an international match to be held in Chicago the following summer, pitting six of the best British players against six of the best Americans, in a mixture of singles and doubles matches.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] This was discussed openly in two articles in the *Chicago Tribune*, but did not come to fruition.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Nevertheless, the following summer, Great Britain—though not under the official auspices of the Lawn Tennis Association—sent three of its best players to compete in several US tournaments.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Their relative poor performances convinced Dwight and other leading officials and figures in American lawn tennis that the time was right for a properly sanctioned international competition.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] This was to be staged in Newcastle in July 1898, but the event never took place as the Americans could not field a sufficiently strong team.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] A reciprocal tour to the U.S. in 1899 amounted to just a single British player travelling overseas, as many of the players were involved in overseas armed conflicts.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] He approached James Dwight with the idea, which was tentatively agreed, and he ordered an appropriate sterling silver punchbowl trophy from Shreve, Crump & Low, purchasing it from his own funds for about US$1,000.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] They in turn commissioned a classically styled design from William B.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Durgin's of Concord, New Hampshire, crafted by the Englishman Rowland Rhodes.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Research has shown this to be a myth, similar in its exaggeration of a single individual's efforts within a highly complex long-term development to the myths of William Webb Ellis and Abner Doubleday, who have both been wrongly credited with inventing rugby and baseball, respectively.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Davis nevertheless went on to become a prominent politician in the United States in the 1920s, serving as US Secretary of War from 1925 to 1929 and as Governor-General of the Philippines from 1929 to 1932.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The first match, between the United States and Britain (competing as the "British Isles"), was held at the Longwood Cricket Club in Boston, Massachusetts in 1900.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The American team, of which Dwight Davis was captain, surprised the British by winning the first three matches.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The following year the two countries did not compete, but the US won the match in 1902 and Britain won the following four matches.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] By 1905 the event expanded to include Belgium, Austria, France, and Australasia, a combined team from Australia and New Zealand that competed together until 1914.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The competition was initially titled the *International Lawn Tennis Challenge* although it soon became known as the *Davis Cup*, after Dwight Davis' trophy.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The Davis Cup competition was initially played as a challenge cup.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] All teams competed against one another for the right to face the previous year's champion in the final round.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Beginning in 1923, the world's teams were split into two zones: the "America Zone" and the "Europe Zone".
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The winners of the two zones met in the *Inter-Zonal Zone* ("INZ") to decide which national team would challenge the defending champion for the cup.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The zone names reflected where the matches were played rather than the nations' home continents; for example, in the 1925 Europe Zone, India lost to Belgium in Brussels, while in the America Zone, Japan played Spain and Australia in the United States.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 1955 a third zone, the "Eastern Zone", was added.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Because there were three zones, the winner of one of the three zones received a bye in the first round of the INZ challenger rounds.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 1966, the "Europe Zone" was split into two zones, "Europe Zone A" and "Europe Zone B", so the winners of the four zones competed in the INZ challenger rounds.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] From 1950 to 1967, Australia dominated the competition, winning the Cup 15 times in 18 years.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Beginning in 1972, the format was changed to a knockout competition, so that the defending champion was required to compete in all rounds, and the Davis Cup was awarded to the champion.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Up until 1973, the Davis Cup had only ever been won by the United States, Great Britain/British Isles, France and Australia/Australasia.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Their domination was eventually broken in 1974 when South Africa and India made the final; however, the final was scratched and South Africa was awarded the cup after India refused to travel to South Africa in protest of South Africa's apartheid policies.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The following year saw the first actual final between two "outsider" nations, when Sweden beat Czechoslovakia 3–2, and since then, many other countries have gone on to capture the trophy.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] All contract professionals were not allowed to play in the Davis Cup until 1973.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The tennis stars who turned professional prior to the Open Era (pre-1968) were not allowed to compete in the Davis Cup despite the fact that the Grand Slam tournaments and most tennis tournaments became Open Era events in 1968.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] From 1968 national registered professionals were allowed to compete under the control of their national tennis associations.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 1973 Australian players like Rod Laver and Ken Rosewall were allowed to play in the Davis Cup for the first time since 1962 (for Laver) and since 1956 (for Rosewall).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 1981, a tiered system of competition was created, in which the 16 best national teams compete in the *World Group* and all other national teams compete in one of four groups in one of three regional zones.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The eight losers of the first round of the World Group played in a relegation match, with the winner staying in the next year's world group and the loser relegated to a regional zone.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The winner of each regional zone group qualified for the next year's World Group.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 1989, the relegation round was renamed to the "World Group Qualifying Round" and expanded to include a total of 16 teams.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The losers of the first round of the World Group were matched against the winners of the regional zone groups, which were each split into two subgroups, and the winner of the match qualified for the subsequent year's World Group.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] That same year, the tiebreak was introduced into Davis Cup competition, and from 2016 it is used in all five sets.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In 2018, World Tennis voted to change the format of the competition from 2019 onwards, changing it to an 18-team event to happen at the end of the season, with 71% of World Tennis member federations voting in favour of the change.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The new format, backed by footballer Gerard Piqué and Japanese businessman Hiroshi Mikitani, was likened to a world cup of tennis and was designed to be more attractive to sponsors and broadcasters.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Opposing federations included those from Australia, Germany, and Great Britain.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Support for the reform was also mixed among current and former players, with some such as Novak Djokovic and Rafael Nadal being in favour of the new format, but others such as Rod Laver, Lucas Pouille and Roger Federer being opposed.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] On 12 January 2023, World Tennis announced that the partnership with the new promoter would end, with World Tennis taking back control of the Davis Cup.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Russia and Belarus were suspended after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Starting with the 2026 Davis Cup, the Swedish online gaming company Betsson was announced as the tournament's official sports betting partner.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Originally manufactured for a price of £700, today's Davis Cup is made from 217 ounces of silver and standing at 13 inches tall with a diameter of 18 inches, sitting on top of three plinths.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The Davis Cup Trophy is now restored and repaired by Royal Warrant holding goldsmiths and silversmiths, Thomas Lyte.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The trophy is also known by its nickname "Salad Bowl".
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The 18 best national teams are assigned to the World Group and compete annually for the Davis Cup.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Nations which are not in the World Group compete in one of three regional zones (Americas, Asia/Oceania, and Europe/Africa).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The competition is spread over four weekends during the year.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Each elimination round between competing nations is held in one of the countries, and is played as the best of five matches (4 singles, 1 doubles).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] World Tennis determines the host countries for all possible matchups before each year's tournament.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The World Group is the top group and includes the world's best 18 national teams.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Teams in the World Group play a four-round elimination event.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Teams are seeded based on a ranking system released by World Tennis, taking into account previous years' results.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The defending champion and runner-up are always the top two seeds in the event.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The losers of the first-round matches are sent to the World Group playoff round, where they play along with winners from Group I of the regional zones.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The playoff round winners play in the World Group for the next year's competition, while the losers play in Group I of their respective regional zone.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Each of the three regional zones is divided into four groups.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Groups I and II play elimination rounds, with the losing teams facing relegation to the next-lower group.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The teams in Groups III and those in Group IV play a round-robin event with promotion and relegation.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] For the 2019 edition, the format of the cup is changed.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The main modification is the World Group taking place at one location and in one week, with eighteen teams divided in six round-robin groups of three teams each, with the winners of the groups and the two best second places advancing to quarterfinals.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The series between the teams in this stage will feature two singles matches and one doubles match, instead of the best-of-5 series, with the matches changing from best of 5 sets to best of 3.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] As the World Group will now take place as one single competition, this event has been named as the Davis Cup Finals.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The lower zone groups I and II will be composed of single ties deciding promotion or relegation.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Note: The total number of nations in Group One is 24.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] However, the distribution among the three zones may vary each year, according to the number of nations promoted or relegated between Group One and the World Group.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The number of nations in the World Group and Group One together is 22 from Euro/Africa Zone, 9 from Americas Zone and 9 from Asia/Oceania Zone.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] As in other cup competitions *tie* is used in the Davis Cup to mean an elimination round.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In the Davis Cup, the word *rubber* means an individual match.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In the annual World Group competition, 16 nations compete in eight first-round ties; the eight winners compete in four quarterfinal ties; the four winners compete in two semifinal ties; and the two winners compete in the final tie.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Each tie consists of five rubbers, which are played in three days (usually on Friday, Saturday, and Sunday).
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The winner of the tie is the nation which wins three or more of the five rubbers in the tie.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] On the first day, the first two rubbers are singles, which are generally played by each nation's two best available singles players.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] On the second day, the doubles rubber is played.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] On the third day, the final two rubbers are typically *reverse singles*, in which the first-day contestants usually play again, but they swap opponents from the first day's singles rubbers.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] However, in certain circumstances, the team captain may replace one or two of the players who played the singles on Friday by other players who were nominated for the tie.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] For example, if the tie has already been decided in favour of one of the teams, it is common for younger or lower-ranked team members to play the remaining *dead rubbers* in order for them to gain Davis Cup experience.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Since 2011, if a nation has a winning 3–1 lead after the first reverse single match and that match has gone to four sets or more, then the remaining reverse single match which is a dead rubber is not played.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] All five rubbers are played if one nation has a winning 3–0 lead after the doubles match.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Ties are played at a venue chosen by one of the competing countries.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The right of choice is given on an alternating basis.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Therefore, countries play in the country where the last tie between the teams was not held.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In case the two countries have not met since 1970, lots are drawn to determine the host country.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Prior to each tie, the captain (non-playing coach appointed by the national association) nominates a squad of four players and decides who will compete in the tie.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] On the day before play starts, the order of play for the first day is drawn at random.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In the past, teams could substitute final day singles players only in case of injury or illness, verified by a doctor, but current rules permit the captain to designate any player to play the last two singles rubbers, provided that no first day matchup is repeated.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] There is no restriction on which of the playing team members may play the doubles rubber: the two singles players, two other players (usually doubles specialists) or a combination.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Each rubber is normally played as best of five sets.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] Since 2016, all sets use a tiebreak at 6–6 if necessary (formerly, the fifth set usually had no tiebreaker, so play continued until one side won by two games e.g.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] However, if a team has clinched the tie before all five rubbers have been completed, the remaining rubbers may be shortened to best of three sets, with a tiebreak if necessary to decide all three sets.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] In Group III and Group IV competitions, each tie consists only of three rubbers, which include two singles and one doubles rubber, which is played in a single day.
[src:davis-cup/davis-cup] The rubbers are in the best of three sets format, with a tie breaker if necessary to decide all three sets.
